Preliminary Tasks

#read in the Stations Data about locations of each of the stations
Stations <- mosaic::read.file("http://tiny.cc/dcf/DC-Stations.csv")
## Reading data with read.csv()
#read in the Trips data about the rental history over Q4 of 2014
data_site <- "http://tiny.cc/dcf/2014-Q4-Trips-History-Data.rds"
Trips <- readRDS(gzcon(url(data_site)))

We are only working with a few variables from each dataset:
From Stations:

  • lat and long: the latitude and longitude of the station, respectively

  • name: the name of the station

From Trips:

  • sstation: name of the station where the bike was checked out

  • estation: name of the station where the bike was returned

  • client: indicates whether the customer is a “regular” user who has paid the yearly membership fee or a “casual” user who has paid a fee for a 5-day membership

  • sdate: date and time of checkout

  • edate: date and time of return

Given: distribution of times that bikes were checked out-

Trips %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=sdate)) +
  geom_density(fill="blue")

Problem A.1- How long?

Your Turn: Make a box and whisker plot showing the distribution of the duration of rental events, broken down by the client type. The duration of the rental can be calculated as as.numeric(edate - sdate).

Trips <- Trips %>%
  mutate(howLongMins = as.numeric(edate-sdate)/60)  #divide by 60 to get minutes- initial form is seconds
Trips <- Trips %>%
  filter(howLongMins <= 100)  #100 minutes was a reasonalbe point to cut it off at
Trips %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=client, y=howLongMins)) +
  geom_boxplot(mapping=NULL, data=NULL, stat="boxplot", position="dodge", outlier.color="blue")

Problem A.2- When are bikes used?

We will use a package called lubridate to get the discrete components of a date.

  • The day of the year (1-365): lubridate::yday(sdate)

  • The day of the week (Sunday to Saturday): lubridate::wday(sdate)

  • The hour of day: lubridate::hour(sdate)

  • The minute of the hour: lubridate::minute(sdate)

Your Turn: Make histograms or density plots of each of the above discrete components.

The Day of the Year:
Trips %>%
  mutate(Y = lubridate::yday(sdate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Y)) +
  geom_density(fill="blue")

This shows us that bike rentals decrease as the winter goes on.

The Day of the Week:
Trips %>%
  mutate(W = lubridate::wday(sdate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=W)) +
  geom_histogram(fill="blue") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1:7))

This shows us that a majority of people rent bikes during the week to go to work presumably…

The Hour of Day:
Trips %>%
  mutate(H = lubridate::hour(sdate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=H)) +
  geom_density(fill="blue") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks= c(0:23))

This shows us that the peak hours of the day for rentals are around rush hour start and end.

The Minute of the Hour:
Trips %>%
  mutate(M = lubridate::minute(sdate)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=M)) +
  geom_density(fill="blue")

This shows us that the amount of rentals is pretty evenly distributed over the hour.

Problem A.3- How far?

Find the distance between each pair of staions. You know the position from the lat and long variables in Stations. This is enough informatino to find the distance. The calculation has been implemented in the haversine() function.

source("http://tiny.cc/dcf/haversine.R")

haversine() is a transformation function. To use it, create a data table where a case is a pair of stations and there are variabels for the latitude and longitude of the starting station and the ending station. To do this, join the Station data to itself. The following statements show how to create appropriately named variables for joining.

Simple <- Stations %>%
  select(name, lat, long) %>%
  rename(sstation=name)
Simple2 <- Simple %>%
  rename(estation=sstation, lat2=lat, long2=long)
#looking at the head of both tables...
head(Simple, 5)

The joining of Simple and Simple2 should match every station to every other station. This sort of matching does not make use of any matching variables; everything is matched to everything else. This is called a full outer join.
First, try the full outer join on just a few cases from each table- for example: 4 from the left and 3 from the right.

merge(head(Simple, 4), head(Simple2, 3), by=NULL)

Now let’s do the real thing. They pose a hypothetical situation to prove our knowledge of the actions of a full outer join. Their case is that if there are 347 cases in the Stations data table, how many will there be in a full outer join of the two tables. The answer is 120409. With every station being matched to every other station, that would create \(347^{2}\) cases.

StationPairs <- merge(Simple, Simple2, by=NULL)

Checking the result for sensibility- make a histogram of the station-to-station distances and explain where it looks like what you would expect. (Hint: from one end of D.C. to the other is about 14.1 miles.)

PairDistances <- StationPairs %>%
  mutate(distance = haversine(lat, long, lat2, long2)) %>%
  select(sstation, estation, distance)

Once you have PairDistances, you can join it with Trips to calculate the start-to-end distance of each trip. Use an inner_join.

RideDists <- Trips %>%
  inner_join(PairDistances)
## Joining, by = c("sstation", "estation")

Your Turn: Display the distribution of the ride distances of the rides. Compare it to the distances between pairs of stations. Are they similar?

#Ride Distances
ggplot( data = RideDists, aes(x = distance)) + geom_density(adjust=1) + labs(title="") + theme(legend.position="right")

#Pair Distances
ggplot( data = PairDistances, aes(x = distance)) + geom_density(adjust=5) + labs(title="") + theme(legend.position="right")

The distributions are similar. This is probably because people pick up bikes at one location at the beginning of their day and return them to another location when they get to the station nearest their destination. Then they proceed to pick up their bikes, ride them back to where they came from, and drop them off for good. So the distance traveled is the distance between the stations, so to me it makes sense that the distributions are similar.

Problem A.4- Mapping the Stations

Install leaflet to draw detailed maps.

devtools::install_github("rstudio/leaflet")

leaflet works much like ggplot() but provides special facilities for maps. Simple map:

library(leaflet)
## 
## Attaching package: 'leaflet'
## The following object is masked from 'package:mosaic':
## 
##     evalFormula
stationMap <-
  leaflet(Stations) %>%
  addTiles() %>%         #add the map
  addCircleMarkers(radius=2, color="red") %>%
  setView(-77.04, 38.9, zoom=12)
## Assuming 'long' and 'lat' are longitude and latitude, respectively
stationMap
